"""
mkt-context | 1 Chronicles 16-17 | fill
Covers missing verses: ch16 (all except v8, v39), ch17 (all except v3)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-1chronicles-16-17-fill.py
"""
import json, pathlib

def load_comm(path):
    p = pathlib.Path(path)
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(path, data):
    pathlib.Path(path).write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=2))

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DATA = {
"16": {
"1": '<p>Bringing the ark to Jerusalem is the culmination of what was interrupted in ch13 when Uzzah was struck dead at the threshing floor of Chidon. David&#8217;s second attempt (ch15) followed the Torah prescription: Levites bearing the ark on poles (Exod 25:14; Num 4:15). The tent David pitched for the ark was distinct from the Mosaic tabernacle, which remained at Gibeon (v39). Two concurrent worship sites&#8212;Zion and Gibeon&#8212;coexisted during David&#8217;s reign, a situation unique in Israelite history and not fully resolved until Solomon built the temple.</p>',
"2": '<p>David&#8217;s priestly function here&#8212;offering sacrifices and blessing the people &#8220;in the name of the LORD&#8221;&#8212;operated within a special Davidic royal-priestly context. The Chronicler presents David performing duties normally reserved for priests (contrast 2 Chr 26:18 where Uzziah is struck for presuming priestly functions). This royal blessing echoes Melchizedek (Gen 14:19) and anticipates the eschatological king-priest figure. The blessing &#8220;in the name of the LORD&#8221; is the priestly benediction formula of Num 6:24&#8211;26.</p>',
"3": '<p>The distribution of food to every Israelite man and woman&#8212;loaf of bread, piece of meat (<em>&#x2018;eshpar</em>), and raisin cake (<em>&#x2018;ashishah</em>)&#8212;echoes festal covenant meals. The raisin cake (<em>&#x2018;ashishah</em>) appears in Hos 3:1 associated with pagan cult meals, but here it functions as joyful covenant celebration. The communal meal distributed by the king recalls both the manna provision in the wilderness and anticipates the messianic banquet theme (Isa 25:6). Distributing rations to the entire community was also an ANE royal gesture of patronage at temple dedications.</p>',
"4": '<p>David establishes a new worship order: Levites appointed specifically &#8220;to invoke&#8221; (<em>lizkir</em>), &#8220;to give thanks&#8221; (<em>lehod&#333;t</em>), and &#8220;to praise&#8221; (<em>lehallel</em>). These three Hebrew terms form the basic vocabulary of Israel&#8217;s liturgical practice. The <em>zikkaron</em> (memorial invocation) concept was rooted in calling God to remember his covenant (Exod 2:24). This appointment represents the institutionalization of responsive worship&#8212;a standing liturgical office&#8212;rather than ad hoc praise. The Chronicler presents David as the architect of Israel&#8217;s worship system, equivalent in importance to his role as military leader.</p>',
"5": '<p>The list of Levitical musicians places Asaph as chief (<em>ber&#333;&#x2019;sh</em>). Asaph was the founder of one of the great guilds of temple musicians; twelve psalms are ascribed to him (Ps 50; 73&#8211;83). The instrument list&#8212;lyres (<em>nevelim</em>), harps (<em>kinn&#333;r&#333;t</em>), and cymbals (<em>mets&#803;iltayim</em>)&#8212;represents the core of Levitical instrumental worship. Obed-edom appears again here as a gatekeeper (cf. 13:14 where he hosted the ark for three months). His elevation to the worship roster shows honor restored after the ark&#8217;s difficult transit.</p>',
"6": '<p>The priests Benaiah and Jahaziel are assigned to blow trumpets (<em>h&#803;ats&#803;&#333;ts&#803;er&#333;t</em>) continually before the ark. The silver trumpets (<em>h&#803;ats&#803;&#333;ts&#803;er&#333;t</em>) were priestly instruments distinct from the ram&#8217;s horn (<em>sh&#333;far</em>); they were used for signaling in battle and calling assemblies (Num 10:1&#8211;10). Their &#8220;continual&#8221; sounding before the ark reflects the perpetual nature of the ark&#8217;s sacred status. This liturgical detail is the kind of institutional precision the Chronicler preserves as essential background for his postexilic audience rebuilding temple worship.</p>',
"7": '<p>The phrase &#8220;on that day David first appointed Asaph and his brothers to give thanks to the LORD&#8221; introduces the inaugural psalm (vv8&#8211;36). The word &#8220;first&#8221; (<em>ba-y&#333;m hahu&#x2019;</em>) signals a foundational institution&#8212;this is the originating act of organized Levitical praise. The Chronicler&#8217;s audience, who were rebuilding postexilic worship, would hear in this &#8220;first appointment&#8221; both the historical precedent and the model for their own re-establishment of liturgical practices in the Second Temple period.</p>',
"9": '<p>The call to &#8220;sing praises to him; tell of all his wondrous works&#8221; (<em>sihu bekhol-nifle&#x2019;otav</em>) uses the verb <em>si&#x2019;ah</em> (to meditate, speak, tell). This is the same verb used in Ps 105:2 (this psalm&#8217;s parallel source) and Ps 145:5. The term &#8220;wondrous works&#8221; (<em>nifle&#x2019;ot</em>) in Hebrew refers specifically to the saving acts of God in history&#8212;the Exodus, the Red Sea crossing, the wilderness provision. Telling these deeds was not merely narrating history but a covenantal act of witness that renewed the community&#8217;s identity as the recipients of God&#8217;s power.</p>',
"10": '<p>&#8220;Glory in his holy name&#8221; (<em>hithhallelu beshem qodsho</em>)&#8212;the reflexive-intensive form of <em>hallel</em> (praise) means to boast in or exult in. The &#8220;holy name&#8221; in ANE context was more than a label; it was the expression of character and presence. The divine name YHWH was the disclosure of God&#8217;s identity at Sinai (Exod 3:14&#8211;15; 6:2&#8211;3). To &#8220;glory in his holy name&#8221; was to locate one&#8217;s identity and honor in the character of Israel&#8217;s God&#8212;a countercultural act in a world where nations gloried in their military gods.</p>',
"11": '<p>&#8220;Seek the LORD and his strength; seek his presence continually&#8221; (<em>dirshu YHWH ve&#x2019;uzzo, baqshu fanav tamid</em>). The verb <em>darash</em> (seek, inquire) was the technical term for consulting God through the oracle, prophet, or sanctuary (cf. 1 Chr 10:13&#8211;14 where Saul&#8217;s sin was failing to seek the LORD). &#8220;His strength&#8221; (the ark, Ps 78:61; 132:8) and &#8220;his presence&#8221; (the ark as the locus of divine presence) are ark-language, making this invitation specifically tied to worship at the new ark-shrine David has established.</p>',
"12": '<p>The call to &#8220;remember the wondrous works he has done, his miracles and the judgments he has uttered&#8221; is the formal act of <em>zikkaron</em>&#8212;covenant remembrance. The &#8220;judgments he has uttered&#8221; (<em>mishpetey fiv</em>) refers to God&#8217;s declarations against Egypt in the plagues (Exod 6:6; 7:4). For the postexilic Chronicler&#8217;s audience, this remembrance was not nostalgic but constitutive&#8212;each generation renewed its covenant identity by reciting God&#8217;s acts, preventing the &#8220;forgetting&#8221; that the Deuteronomic tradition identified as the root of apostasy.</p>',
"13": '<p>&#8220;O offspring of Israel his servant, children of Jacob, his chosen ones!&#8221; The address to Israel as &#8220;seed of Israel his servant&#8221; (<em>zera&#x2019; Yisra&#x2019;el &#x2018;avdo</em>) uses the covenant-identity formula. &#8220;His servant&#8221; (<em>&#x2018;avdo</em>) is the title of the patriarchs and Moses in the covenant context (Deut 34:5; Josh 24:29). &#8220;His chosen ones&#8221; (<em>behirav</em>)&#8212;the plural form&#8212;frames election as communal and ongoing, not merely individual and past. For the postexilic community hearing this, the claim to be &#8220;chosen&#8221; after exile required this kind of deliberate liturgical reassertion of identity.</p>',
"14": '<p>&#8220;He is the LORD our God; his judgments are in all the earth.&#8221; The universalism of this statement is significant in context: Israel&#8217;s God is not the god of a territory or ethnic group but the one whose judicial authority (<em>mishpat&#803;im</em>) extends over the entire earth. This universal scope was the ground for the Great Commission of the psalm (&#8220;make known his deeds among the peoples,&#8221; v8)&#8212;one announces the LORD&#8217;s deeds universally precisely because his lordship is universal. ANE treaty language used &#8220;judgments&#8221; for the stipulations that bound vassals to their overlord.</p>',
"15": '<p>&#8220;Remember his covenant forever, the word he commanded for a thousand generations.&#8221; The term &#8220;thousand generations&#8221; (<em>elef dor</em>) appears also in Deut 7:9 in the context of covenant faithfulness. The number is hyperbolic in the ANE idiom for absolute permanence. The command to &#8220;remember&#8221; (<em>zakar</em>) the covenant was the foundational act of covenant renewal in Israel&#8217;s liturgical calendar, making this verse both a historical reference and a present summons to the worshiping community.</p>',
"16": '<p>The covenant made with Abraham (<em>berit</em>) and the sworn oath to Isaac (<em>shevuato leYits&#803;haq</em>) are the Abrahamic covenant of Genesis 12, 15, 17, and 22. The terms &#8220;covenant&#8221; (<em>berit</em>) and &#8220;sworn oath&#8221; (<em>shevuah</em>) represent two different legal-covenantal forms: the grant-type covenant (unconditional) and the sworn-oath form (invoking divine self-curse for violation). Their combination signals the absolute reliability of the Abrahamic promise&#8212;it is both formally contracted and divinely sworn.</p>',
"17": '<p>The confirmation of the Abrahamic covenant &#8220;to Jacob as a statute (<em>hok</em>), to Israel as an everlasting covenant (<em>berit &#x2018;olam</em>)&#8221; adds the legal category of <em>hok</em>&#8212;a decreed ordinance, a fixed regulation. The phrase &#8220;everlasting covenant&#8221; (<em>berit &#x2018;olam</em>) is one of the most significant in the OT (cf. Gen 9:16 for Noah; Gen 17:7 for Abraham; 2 Sam 23:5 for David). The repetition of this covenant across the patriarchal chain&#8212;Abraham, Isaac, Jacob&#8212;demonstrates its progressive confirmation, not mere repetition.</p>',
"18": '<p>The covenant promise &#8220;to you I will give the land of Canaan as your portion for an inheritance&#8221; uses the land-grant formula common in ANE royal grants. Archaeological evidence from the second millennium BCE shows land grants where a suzerain gives land to a loyal vassal with the formula &#8220;I give you this land.&#8221; The Abrahamic promise is structured as a royal grant&#8212;the Great King (YHWH) bestowing territory on his vassal people. The term &#8220;portion&#8221; (<em>h&#803;evel</em>) literally means &#8220;measuring line,&#8221; indicating land surveyed and formally allocated.</p>',
"19": '<p>&#8220;When you were few in number, of little account, and strangers in the land&#8221;&#8212;the description of the patriarchal situation as numerically insignificant (<em>me&#x2018;at misp&#803;ar</em>) and as resident aliens (<em>ger</em>) is an important ANE social category. The <em>ger</em> (sojourner) had no land rights, no tribal or clan protection, and no legal standing in a foreign territory. The covenant promise is all the more remarkable given this social vulnerability: God chose to bind himself in covenant to people with no political leverage or demographic strength.</p>',
"20": '<p>&#8220;When they wandered from nation to nation, from one kingdom to another people&#8221; describes the patriarchal migrations: Abraham in Canaan, Egypt, and the Negev; Isaac in Gerar; Jacob in Haran and Egypt. The itinerant nature of the patriarchal period is confirmed by archaeology: the Middle Bronze Age (ca. 2000&#8211;1550 BCE) shows nomadic and semi-nomadic peoples moving through the Fertile Crescent. The verb &#8220;wandered&#8221; (<em>halakh</em>, to walk) is used deliberately; it is the same verb as Abraham&#8217;s call to &#8220;walk before me&#8221; (Gen 17:1).</p>',
"21": '<p>&#8220;He allowed no one to oppress them; he rebuked kings on their account&#8221; refers specifically to the incidents of Gen 12:17 (Pharaoh plagued for taking Sarah), Gen 20:3&#8211;7 (God warning Abimelech in a dream), and Gen 26:28&#8211;29 (Abimelech making peace with Isaac under divine pressure). The pattern of a &#8220;rebuke&#8221; (<em>yiga&#x2018;ar</em>) of kings shows YHWH operating as a suzerain protecting his covenant people from encroachment by other political powers&#8212;extraordinary given the patriarchs&#8217; vulnerable <em>ger</em> status.</p>',
"22": '<p>&#8220;Touch not my anointed ones; do my prophets no harm!&#8221; The term &#8220;anointed&#8221; (<em>meshiah&#803;&#803;im</em>) here applies to the patriarchs&#8212;a striking use since formal anointing of kings had not yet begun. In context, &#8220;anointed&#8221; means &#8220;set apart, consecrated&#8221; by covenant relationship. The word &#8220;prophets&#8221; (<em>nevi&#x2019;im</em>) applied to Abraham (Gen 20:7) indicates a pre-classical prophetic role. The divine protection formula here became a key liturgical text cited in Rabbinic literature for the special protection of Torah scholars.</p>',
"23": '<p>The shift from addressing Israel (vv13&#8211;22, drawn from Ps 105) to addressing all the earth (vv23&#8211;33, drawn from Ps 96) marks the universal scope of this psalm. &#8220;Proclaim his salvation from day to day&#8221; (<em>basser miy&#333;m ley&#333;m yeshu&#x2018;at&#333;</em>)&#8212;the word <em>basser</em> (proclaim good news) is the verb behind the noun &#8220;gospel&#8221; (Isaiah&#8217;s <em>mevasser</em>, Isa 52:7; 61:1). The daily proclamation of YHWH&#8217;s salvation to all nations is the missionary mandate embedded in Israel&#8217;s worship, not an innovation of the NT.</p>',
"24": '<p>&#8220;Declare his glory among the nations, his marvellous works among all peoples&#8221;&#8212;the vocabulary of universal proclamation (<em>bagoyim, be&#x2018;amim</em>) addresses nations and peoples as the audience of Israel&#8217;s witness. This universalism is characteristic of Ps 96 (likely a Second Temple liturgical text) but also rooted in the Abrahamic promise that &#8220;all nations shall be blessed&#8221; (Gen 12:3). The Chronicler&#8217;s postexilic community would hear in this a mandate for their witness among the nations in whose territories they now lived as scattered exiles.</p>',
"25": '<p>&#8220;For great is the LORD, and greatly to be praised; he is to be feared above all gods&#8221; (<em>ki gadol YHWH umehullal me&#x2019;od venora&#x2019; hu&#x2019; &#x2018;al kol-elohim</em>). The comparative &#8220;above all gods&#8221; does not affirm the existence of other gods but uses the standard ANE polemical form that asserts YHWH&#8217;s supremacy over all rival deities. This formula is found in Ugaritic and Phoenician texts comparing one deity&#8217;s power with others. Israel&#8217;s use of it transforms the idiom: YHWH is incomparable precisely because the rivals are not real gods (v26).</p>',
"26": '<p>&#8220;For all the gods of the peoples are idols (<em>elilim</em>), but the LORD made the heavens.&#8221; The word <em>elilim</em> is a wordplay&#8212;it resembles <em>el</em> (god) but means &#8220;nothings, worthless things.&#8221; The contrast is absolute: the nation-gods are fabricated (<em>elilim</em>), while YHWH is the creator of the heavens. This contrast echoes the polemics of Isa 40&#8211;48 against Babylonian idol-manufacture. The cosmological argument (&#8220;he made the heavens&#8221;) grounds YHWH&#8217;s superiority not in Israel&#8217;s tribal traditions but in the act of creation itself.</p>',
"27": '<p>&#8220;Splendour and majesty are before him; strength and joy are in his dwelling place.&#8221; The terms <em>hod</em> (splendor/majesty) and <em>hadar</em> (majesty/honor) are royal epithets used in the ANE for the aura of divine and royal presence&#8212;sometimes depicted as a radiant cloud or fire. &#8220;His dwelling place&#8221; (<em>bimqom&#333;</em>) is a significant term in the ark narrative context: the ark was the portable divine dwelling. The joy (<em>simh&#803;ah</em>) in the divine dwelling contrasts with the terror of Sinai (Exod 19:16) and emphasizes the celebratory nature of the ark&#8217;s arrival at Zion.</p>',
"28": '<p>The address &#8220;O families of the peoples&#8221; (<em>mishpeh&#333;t ha&#x2018;amim</em>) is strikingly universal&#8212;all family-groups of all peoples are invited to ascribe (<em>havu</em>: give, bring, attribute) glory to YHWH. The term <em>mishpah&#803;ah</em> (family, clan) is the basic unit of kinship organization in the ancient world. Calling all <em>mishpah&#803;ot</em> to worship is a comprehensive call that bridges the distinction between Israel and the nations at the level of basic social units&#8212;the families, not just the nations in their political form.</p>',
"29": '<p>&#8220;Bring an offering and come before him; worship the LORD in the splendour of holiness.&#8221; The &#8220;offering&#8221; (<em>minh&#803;ah</em>) was the tribute-gift presented to a king or deity in the ANE&#8212;it acknowledged the recipient&#8217;s lordship. The phrase &#8220;splendour of holiness&#8221; (<em>hadrat qodesh</em>) may refer to sacred vestments worn in worship (cf. 2 Chr 20:21) or to the holiness-aura of the divine presence. The call for all peoples to bring offerings before YHWH at Zion anticipates the prophetic vision of nations streaming to the mountain of the LORD with gifts (Isa 2:2&#8211;3; 60:3).</p>',
"30": '<p>&#8220;Tremble before him, all the earth! The world is firmly established; it cannot be moved.&#8221; The cosmic stability claim (<em>tikkun tevel bal-timmot</em>) was a significant theological statement in the context of ANE cosmology, where rival creation accounts portrayed the world as the product of divine combat that could theoretically be undone. The Chronicler uses this cosmological stability claim as part of the liturgy&#8212;YHWH&#8217;s creative act is not reversible, and the stability of the cosmos is grounded in his ongoing sovereign will.</p>',
"31": '<p>&#8220;Let the heavens be glad, and let the earth rejoice, and let them say among the nations, &#x2018;The LORD reigns!&#x2019;&#8221; (<em>YHWH malak</em>). The phrase &#8220;the LORD reigns&#8221; (<em>YHWH malak</em>) is the central proclamation of the Enthronement Psalms (Ps 93, 96&#8211;99). The meaning is debated: does it announce a new enthronement (&#8220;the LORD has become king&#8221;) or declare ongoing reign (&#8220;the LORD is king&#8221;)? In the Chronicles context, the arrival of the ark at Zion is the occasion for the proclamation&#8212;YHWH&#8217;s kingship is enacted through his presence among his people in Jerusalem.</p>',
"32": '<p>The cosmic celebration&#8212;sea roaring, fields exulting&#8212;is the standard ANE imagery of creation rejoicing at the enthronement of its divine king. Ugaritic texts describing Baal&#8217;s kingship use similar imagery of seas responding to the king&#8217;s establishment. The psalm deliberately uses this imagery for YHWH, asserting that the cosmic response appropriate to a divine king is owed to Israel&#8217;s God alone. The fields (<em>sadeh</em>) and their produce are described as active celebrants&#8212;creation is not neutral toward its creator.</p>',
"33": '<p>&#8220;Then shall the trees of the forest sing for joy before the LORD, for he comes to judge the earth.&#8221; The coming of YHWH &#8220;to judge the earth&#8221; (<em>lishpot&#803; ha&#x2019;arets</em>) is presented as good news that causes creation to celebrate. In ANE thought, the arrival of the king to &#8220;judge&#8221; (<em>shafat&#803;</em>) meant establishing right order, administering justice, and ending chaos. The trees of the forest singing for joy at the divine judge&#8217;s coming reflects the expectation that divine judgment is restorative, not merely punitive&#8212;it corrects the disorder that oppresses creation.</p>',
"34": '<p>&#8220;Oh give thanks to the LORD, for he is good; for his steadfast love endures forever!&#8221; (<em>ki tov ki le&#x2018;olam h&#803;asdo</em>). This refrain is the most frequently repeated liturgical formula in Israel&#8217;s worship (Ps 106:1; 107:1; 118:1&#8211;4, 29; 136; Ezra 3:11). The combination of <em>tov</em> (good, morally and aesthetically) and <em>h&#803;esed</em> (covenant loyalty, steadfast love) expresses the character of YHWH as a covenant partner. The <em>h&#803;esed</em> that &#8220;endures forever&#8221; (<em>le&#x2018;olam</em>) was the theological anchor of Israel&#8217;s hope through exile&#8212;even when the covenant appeared broken from Israel&#8217;s side, YHWH&#8217;s <em>h&#803;esed</em> did not end.</p>',
"35": '<p>&#8220;Save us, O God of our salvation; gather us and deliver us from among the nations.&#8221; The petition for gathering (<em>kabbet&#803;s&#803;enu</em>) and deliverance from among the nations (<em>me-hagoyim</em>) is particularly resonant in a postexilic setting. The Chronicler&#8217;s audience was living in a diaspora reality; this petition voiced what many Second Temple Jews experienced as their ongoing need. The earlier part of the psalm (vv8&#8211;22) celebrated Abrahamic history; this petition applies it to present circumstances&#8212;the same God who gathered the patriarchs could gather the scattered exiles.</p>',
"36": '<p>The doxology &#8220;Blessed be the LORD, the God of Israel, from everlasting to everlasting!&#8221; with the congregational &#8220;Amen!&#8221; and praise is the formal close of a liturgical unit. The <em>berakhah</em> (blessing) formula closes each of the first four books of the Psalter (Ps 41:13; 72:18&#8211;19; 89:52; 106:48). The &#8220;Amen&#8221; (<em>amen</em>) by the whole people was the formal congregational ratification&#8212;the covenantal &#8220;so be it&#8221; that made the doxology a communal act rather than a solo performance. The phrase &#8220;from everlasting to everlasting&#8221; (<em>min-ha&#x2018;olam ve&#x2018;ad ha&#x2018;olam</em>) encloses God&#8217;s existence in the two infinities of past and future.</p>',
"37": '<p>David establishes the permanent post at the ark in Zion: Asaph and his brothers are to minister &#8220;regularly before the ark, as the daily requirements demanded.&#8221; The phrase &#8220;daily requirements&#8221; (<em>debar-y&#333;m bey&#333;m&#333;</em>) indicates this was a standing institution with set times and procedures, not occasional celebration. The Chronicler&#8217;s precision about liturgical arrangements reflects his concern to show that Second Temple worship patterns are rooted in Davidic institution, not postexilic invention.</p>',
"38": '<p>Obed-edom son of Jeduthun and Hosah are appointed as gatekeepers of the ark-tent. Obed-edom appears three times in chs 13&#8211;16: initially as the host of the ark (13:13&#8211;14, blessed for his hospitality), then as a doorkeeper (15:24), and now as a permanent gatekeeper. His trajectory shows the Levitical honor that accrues from faithful proximity to the divine presence. The sixty-eight kinsmen listed with him indicate a substantial community organized around the ark-shrine.</p>',
"40": '<p>The altar of burnt offering at Gibeon is the Mosaic tabernacle altar&#8212;the bronze altar constructed in the wilderness (Exod 27:1&#8211;8; 38:1&#8211;7). The &#8220;Book of the Law of the LORD&#8221; that specifies the morning and evening offerings is the Torah prescription of Exod 29:38&#8211;42 and Num 28:3&#8211;8. The Chronicler notes that while David created a new worship site at Zion for the ark, the traditional sacrificial system continued at Gibeon in strict Torah compliance. This dual arrangement justified the Solomonic temple as the union of both sites.</p>',
"41": '<p>Heman and Jeduthun are appointed alongside Asaph as the designated thanksgiving leaders. These three guilds&#8212;Asaph, Heman, Jeduthun&#8212;are the three great families of Levitical musicians that organized Second Temple choral worship. The phrase &#8220;chosen and designated by name&#8221; (<em>hanivharim benishmot</em>) emphasizes formal appointment by name, not rotation&#8212;this was permanent, prestigious, and publicly recognized. The formula &#8220;for his steadfast love endures forever&#8221; (<em>ki le&#x2018;olam h&#803;asdo</em>) was their liturgical assignment&#8212;they led the antiphonal refrain.</p>',
"42": '<p>The instruments at Gibeon&#8212;trumpets, cymbals, &#8220;instruments for sacred song&#8221; (<em>klei shir ha&#x2019;elohim</em>)&#8212;were the full array of Levitical music. The phrase &#8220;instruments for sacred song&#8221; is unique here and in Neh 12:36, indicating a specialized category of holy instruments distinct from ordinary music. The sons of Jeduthun assigned as gatekeepers shows that music and security were not separated roles in the Levitical service&#8212;gatekeeping was a liturgical function with its own theology of protecting sacred space.</p>',
"43": '<p>The narrative closure&#8212;all the people departing to their houses, David returning to bless his household&#8212;mirrors the pattern of great covenant ceremonies. The ark&#8217;s installation is followed by the people&#8217;s dispersal to normal life, just as covenant ratification ceremonies ended with participants returning home (cf. Josh 24:28). David&#8217;s household blessing parallels his public blessing of all Israel (v2), showing the king as the mediating point between the divine blessing and the community at every level from nation to family.</p>'
},
"17": {
"1": '<p>David&#8217;s observation&#8212;&#8220;I am living in a house of cedar while the ark of God dwells in a tent&#8221;&#8212;reflects a significant ANE cultural concern: the disparity between royal luxury and divine accommodation was perceived as improper. Cedar was the prestige timber of the ancient world, imported from Lebanon and used exclusively for royal and sacred buildings (cf. 1 Kgs 5&#8211;7). The contrast between David&#8217;s permanent cedar palace and the temporary tent-shrine for the ark created an implicit obligation in ANE royal theology to honor one&#8217;s patron deity with at least equivalent accommodation.</p>',
"2": '<p>Nathan&#8217;s initial affirmative response&#8212;&#8220;Go ahead with everything you have in mind, for God is with you&#8221;&#8212;shows a prophet speaking from human reasoning before receiving divine revelation. Nathan is a genuine prophet (unlike the false prophets of later Kings) yet here speaks without prophetic authorization. The tension between prophetic human judgment and divine correction is significant: the subsequent revelation overturns not Nathan&#8217;s character but his uninspired assessment. The phrase &#8220;God is with you&#8221; (<em>Elohim &#x2018;immak</em>) is the covenant assurance formula (Gen 21:22; 26:3).</p>',
"4": '<p>God&#8217;s correction&#8212;&#8220;You are not to build me a house to dwell in&#8221;&#8212;reverses Nathan&#8217;s initial blessing. The word used for &#8220;house&#8221; (<em>bayit</em>) is the central wordplay of this chapter: it means both &#8220;building/temple&#8221; and &#8220;dynasty/household.&#8221; The divine reply rejects David&#8217;s offer to build God a <em>bayit</em> (temple) and announces that God will instead build David a <em>bayit</em> (dynasty). This literary wordplay on <em>bayit</em> is the structural genius of the Davidic covenant oracle&#8212;the very word in David&#8217;s proposal becomes the vehicle for the greater divine promise.</p>',
"5": '<p>God&#8217;s historical self-presentation&#8212;&#8220;I have never lived in a house from the day I brought Israel up from Egypt until now; I have always moved from tent to tent and from one dwelling to another&#8221;&#8212;establishes the theological point that divine mobility is not a deficiency. The tabernacle tradition emphasized that YHWH was not tied to a fixed location&#8212;he moved with his people through the wilderness. This theological mobility contrasts with ANE state religions where a temple was the deity&#8217;s fixed dwelling. The Deuteronomic theology of divine name-presence (rather than bodily presence) at the temple later refined this point further.</p>',
"6": '<p>The rhetorical question&#8212;&#8220;Did I ever say a single word to any of the judges I appointed to shepherd my people: &#x2018;Why have you not built me a house of cedar?&#x2019;&#8221;&#8212;invokes the period of the Judges as the normative era of divine provision without a temple. The judges are described as appointed to &#8220;shepherd&#8221; (<em>lir&#x2018;ot</em>) Israel&#8212;the shepherd-king motif that applies to David as well (v7). The absence of any divine complaint about a temple during the entire period from Exodus to early monarchy establishes that the temple was God&#8217;s initiative, not a human cultural obligation that Israel had been slow to fulfill.</p>',
"7": '<p>The oracle shifts to direct address: &#8220;I took you from the pasture, from following the flock, to be ruler over my people Israel.&#8221; This shepherd-to-king transformation follows a well-attested ANE pattern: several major rulers claimed to have been called from pastoral life by their deity&#8212;including Hammurabi and Sargon of Akkad. David&#8217;s shepherd origins are not incidental but theologically structured: the shepherd-king who tends YHWH&#8217;s &#8220;flock&#8221; (Israel) is the embodiment of the ideal ruler who cares rather than exploits. The phrase &#8220;my people Israel&#8221; is repeated throughout the oracle to emphasize that David rules on divine commission.</p>',
"8": '<p>&#8220;I have been with you wherever you went, and I cut down all your enemies before you.&#8221; The divine warrior formula&#8212;YHWH going before his anointed to defeat enemies&#8212;is the covenant protection clause. The phrase &#8220;I will make your name as great as the names of the greatest men on earth&#8221; uses the promise language of the Abrahamic covenant (&#8220;I will make your name great,&#8221; Gen 12:2). David&#8217;s fame is presented as covenantal gift, not human achievement&#8212;just as Abraham&#8217;s status was given, not earned.</p>',
"9": '<p>&#8220;I will establish a place for my people Israel and plant them firmly there, so they can live undisturbed in their own home.&#8221; The language of &#8220;planting&#8221; (<em>nata&#x2018;</em>) Israel echoes Exod 15:17 (the Song of Moses: &#8220;You will plant them on the mountain of your inheritance&#8221;) and anticipates the prophetic restoration imagery (Amos 9:15; Isa 60:21). The promise of &#8220;undisturbed&#8221; (<em>lo-yirgazu&#x2018;od</em>, no more trembling) settlement points to a condition of complete security that the wilderness wandering and the period of the Judges had not achieved.</p>',
"10": '<p>The transition&#8212;&#8220;I am telling you that the LORD will build a house for you&#8221;&#8212;is the structural pivot of the oracle. The promise that YHWH will &#8220;build&#8221; David&#8217;s house (<em>bayit</em>&#8212;dynasty) is stated formally here. This reversal of the building initiative from David to God is theologically crucial: the Davidic covenant is an unconditional divine grant, not a bilateral arrangement that David initiated or earned. Comparative ANE material (Hittite treaties, Egyptian royal texts) shows that unconditional divine grants to loyal servants were a recognized covenantal form in the second millennium BCE.</p>',
"11": '<p>&#8220;When the time comes for you to join your ancestors, I will raise up one of your own sons after you, and I will establish his kingdom.&#8221; The phrase &#8220;join your ancestors&#8221; (<em>lalehet &#x2018;im avotekha</em>) is the standard Hebrew idiom for death without the negative connotations of Sheol-imagery&#8212;it emphasizes continuity with the ancestral community. The promise of a son who will succeed is presented as YHWH&#8217;s act of raising up (<em>haqim&#333;ti</em>)&#8212;divine appointment rather than normal royal succession&#8212;elevating the succession above ordinary dynastic politics.</p>',
"12": '<p>&#8220;He is the one who will build a house for me, and I will establish his throne forever.&#8221; The reversal is complete: David cannot build God&#8217;s house, but God will establish the throne of David&#8217;s son forever. The word &#8220;forever&#8221; (<em>&#x2018;ad-&#x2018;olam</em>) appears five times in the Davidic covenant oracle (vv12, 14 [twice], 22, 23), marking its most distinctive characteristic. ANE royal inscriptions promised dynastic continuity to loyal vassals, but usually in temporal terms (&#8220;forever and ever&#8221; was a rhetorical flourish). The theological claim here is different: it is a covenant guarantee backed by divine character.</p>',
"13": '<p>&#8220;I will be his father, and he will be my son&#8221; (<em>ani ehyeh lo le&#x2019;av vehu&#x2019; yihyeh li leven</em>) is adoption language. In ANE royal ideology, the &#8220;father-son&#8221; relationship between a deity and the king was well-established in Egyptian and Mesopotamian texts. Psalm 2:7 quotes this formula as a divine decree of adoption at the king&#8217;s enthronement. The phrase &#8220;I will not remove my steadfast love (<em>h&#803;asdi</em>) from him&#8221; contrasts explicitly with what happened to Saul&#8212;establishing that the Davidic covenant includes a new dimension of unconditional <em>h&#803;esed</em> not operative in the Saulide arrangement.</p>',
"14": '<p>&#8220;I will establish him in my house and over my kingdom forever, and his throne will stand firm forever.&#8221; The phrase &#8220;my house and my kingdom&#8221; is striking&#8212;YHWH speaks of David&#8217;s kingdom as his own. The theological claim is that the Davidic monarchy is not an independent human institution but an extension of divine sovereignty. This identification of the Davidic throne with YHWH&#8217;s own kingship is the basis for the Psalms&#8217; royal theology (Ps 2, 45, 72, 89, 110) and the prophetic expectation that the future Davidic king will reign as God&#8217;s own representative over an eternal kingdom (Isa 9:6&#8211;7; Mic 5:2).</p>',
"15": '<p>&#8220;In keeping with all these words and the full vision, Nathan delivered this message to David.&#8221; The phrase &#8220;full vision&#8221; (<em>kehazzon hazzeh</em>) indicates that Nathan received this oracle in a prophetic vision (<em>h&#803;azon</em>)&#8212;the most elevated form of prophetic reception in Hebrew literature (cf. the h&#803;azon of Isaiah and Obadiah). The care with which Nathan communicated &#8220;all these words and the full vision&#8221; emphasizes the completeness of transmission&#8212;the oracle was not paraphrased or edited but delivered intact, establishing its legal-covenantal status.</p>',
"16": '<p>&#8220;King David went in and sat before the LORD.&#8221; The posture of sitting before the ark is unusual&#8212;Israelite worship typically involved standing or prostrating. The phrase may indicate a formal audience posture before the divine king, similar to how a vassal would sit in the presence of an overlord to receive a decree. David&#8217;s response opens with a double self-deprecation formula: &#8220;Who am I, LORD God, and what is my family?&#8221; This is the standard ANE humility formula when a mortal receives an extraordinary divine favor, acknowledging unworthiness to receive the grant.</p>',
"17": '<p>&#8220;You have spoken of your servant&#8217;s house reaching far into the future, and you have shown me future generations, O God.&#8221; The phrase &#8220;reaching far into the future&#8221; (<em>leminha&#x2018;ol</em>) is obscure in Hebrew (the parallel in 2 Sam 7:19 uses <em>tor adam</em>), but the sense is that the promise extends beyond David&#8217;s own lifetime into an unspecified future. David&#8217;s acknowledgment that God has &#8220;shown me future generations&#8221; indicates prophetic awareness that the oracle reaches beyond his son Solomon&#8212;it is not exhausted by the immediate fulfillment.</p>',
"18": '<p>&#8220;What more can David say to you about the honor you have shown your servant? You know your servant.&#8221; The rhetorical question acknowledges that human language is inadequate to respond to divine favor of this magnitude. &#8220;You know your servant&#8221; (<em>yadata et-&#x2018;avdekha</em>) is an appeal to the divine knowledge of David&#8217;s character&#8212;YHWH chose David with full knowledge of who he was. This appeal to divine omniscience as the ground of the covenant relationship is similar to the Psalms&#8217; use of divine knowledge as the basis for prayer (Ps 139).</p>',
"19": '<p>&#8220;LORD, for your servant&#8217;s sake and according to your own heart&#8217;s purpose (<em>lev</em>), you have done this great thing.&#8221; The phrase &#8220;your own heart&#8217;s purpose&#8221; (<em>belibbeka</em>) is theologically significant: the Davidic covenant originates in the divine will alone, not in any external obligation or human merit. The &#8220;great things&#8221; (<em>hagdullah hazot</em>) that God has revealed are described as &#8220;making known all these great promises&#8221;&#8212;the oracle itself is the great act, not merely a promise about future great acts. The revelation of the covenant is already a saving event.</p>',
"20": '<p>&#8220;LORD, there is no one like you&#8212;there is no God but you&#8212;as everything we have heard with our own ears confirms.&#8221; David&#8217;s doxology uses the incomparability formula (<em>&#x2019;en kamokha</em>) common in Psalms (Ps 35:10; 71:19; 89:6&#8211;8) and the prophets (Isa 40:18, 25; 44:7). The grounding of monotheism in historical experience&#8212;&#8220;as we have heard with our own ears&#8221;&#8212;rather than philosophical argument is characteristic of OT theology: Israel&#8217;s confession of one God is rooted in the recital of what YHWH has uniquely done in history.</p>',
"21": '<p>&#8220;Who is like your people Israel&#8212;the one nation on earth that God set out to redeem as his own people?&#8221; David&#8217;s prayer matches the psalm&#8217;s universal scope with Israel&#8217;s particular election. The phrasing &#8220;God set out to redeem as his own people&#8221; (<em>asher halakh haelohim lifdot-lo le&#x2018;am</em>) uses the Exodus vocabulary of redemption (<em>pada&#x2018;</em>&#8212;to ransom, buy back) applied to Israel&#8217;s unique status. The Exodus was the paradigmatic redemption event; the Davidic covenant now adds a royal dimension to the same redeemed community.</p>',
"22": '<p>&#8220;You established Israel as your own people forever, and you, LORD, became their God.&#8221; This covenant formula&#8212;&#8220;they shall be my people and I will be their God&#8221;&#8212;is the most fundamental statement of the Sinai covenant (Exod 6:7; Lev 26:12; Jer 31:33). David&#8217;s prayer incorporates the Mosaic covenant formula into his response to the Davidic covenant, showing that the two covenants are not separate but cumulative&#8212;the Davidic covenant is built on and extends the Sinai structure, not replacing it.</p>',
"23": '<p>&#8220;Now, LORD, let the promise you have spoken about your servant and his house stand firm forever. Act as you have said.&#8221; David&#8217;s petition that the oracle be fulfilled is itself a form of covenant engagement&#8212;the recipient of the grant calling the grantor to enact what was promised. In ANE treaty contexts, invoking the terms of the grant before the divine guarantor was a recognized legal act. David&#8217;s prayer is not doubt about the promise but the formal covenantal act of claiming it.</p>',
"24": '<p>&#8220;May it stand firm, and may your name be made great forever.&#8221; The Davidic covenant serves a double purpose: establishing the dynasty and magnifying the divine name. The phrase &#8220;The LORD of hosts, the God of Israel, is Israel&#8217;s God&#8221; (<em>YHWH ts&#803;eva&#x2019;ot Elohey Yisra&#x2019;el Elohim leyisra&#x2019;el</em>) is the full divine title used in the ark traditions and the temple theology. The title &#8220;LORD of hosts&#8221; (<em>YHWH ts&#803;eva&#x2019;ot</em>) means YHWH of the divine armies&#8212;the warrior-king whose throne is the ark.</p>',
"25": '<p>&#8220;For you, my God, have revealed (<em>galita et-ozen</em>) to your servant that you will build him a house.&#8221; The phrase <em>galita et-ozen</em> (literally &#8220;uncovered the ear&#8221;) is a Hebrew idiom for confidential disclosure&#8212;bending close to whisper in someone&#8217;s ear. It is used for intimate prophetic revelation (1 Sam 9:15; Ruth 4:4). David recognizes that the Davidic covenant is not a public decree but an intimate divine disclosure&#8212;which is why it fills him with such personal gratitude: &#8220;your servant has found the courage to pray to you.&#8221;</p>',
"26": '<p>&#8220;Now, LORD, you are God, and you have made this good promise to your servant.&#8221; The affirmation &#8220;you are God&#8221; (<em>attah hu&#x2019; haElohim</em>) is a formal acknowledgment of divine identity&#8212;the same formula used by Elijah at Carmel (1 Kgs 18:37) and in Nehemiah 9:7. It functions as a covenantal confession. The phrase &#8220;you have made this good promise&#8221; (<em>dibarta al-&#x2018;avdekha et-hattovah hazzot</em>) uses <em>dabar</em> (speak, word) in the sense of a performative utterance: God&#8217;s speaking the promise constitutes it&#8212;the oracle is not merely information but covenant enactment.</p>',
"27": '<p>David&#8217;s closing petition&#8212;&#8220;please be pleased to bless the house of your servant, that it may stand before you forever&#8221;&#8212;returns to the language of divine blessing (<em>barakh</em>). The phrase &#8220;may it stand before you forever&#8221; (<em>lifanekha le&#x2018;olam</em>) echoes the oracle&#8217;s repeated &#8220;forever&#8221; (<em>&#x2018;olam</em>). David&#8217;s prayer does not merely ask for personal blessing but for covenant confirmation: that the divine word spoken through Nathan would be permanently ratified in history. The final clause&#8212;&#8220;for you, LORD, have blessed it, and it will be blessed forever&#8221;&#8212;expresses the ultimate confidence of covenant faith: God&#8217;s promise is its own guarantee.</p>'
}
}

def main():
    out_path = "data/commentary/mkt-context/1chronicles.json"
    existing = load_comm(out_path)
    before = sum(len(existing.get(c, {})) for c in DATA)
    merge_comm(existing, DATA)
    after = sum(len(existing.get(c, {})) for c in DATA)
    save_comm(out_path, existing)
    added = after - before
    print(f"  wrote {out_path}")
    for c in ['16','17']:
        print(f"  ch{c}: {len(existing.get(c,{}))} entries")
    print(f"1chronicles mkt-context ch16-17 fill: added {added} verses")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
